[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "He built Elath.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The pronoun is emphatic; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in contrast with his father. “Built,” either ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "rebuilt",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fortified.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The verse is in close connection with the preceding narrative. Amaziah perhaps had not vigorously prosecuted the conquest of Edom, having been greatly weakened by his defeat in the struggle with Jehoash. He may even have suffered some further losses at the hands of the Edomites; and this, as Thenius supposes may have led to the conspiracy which brought about his death and the accession of his son. The warlike youth Uzziah took the field at once, and pushed his victorious arms to the southern extremity of Edom, the port of Elath (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and thus restored the state of things which had existed under Solomon and Jehoshaphat.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After that the king slept—i.e., immediately after the murder of Amaziah. Thenius explains the verse with most success, but this clause is still somewhat surprising.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "After that the king slept",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", immediately after the murder of Amaziah. Thenius explains the verse with most success, but this clause is still somewhat surprising.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Kings 14:22",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 14:22",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He built Elath — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Repaired and fortified it; for it was built before, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And restored it to Judah — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "From whom it had revolted with the rest of Edom, in which land it lay, upon the Red sea. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "After that the king — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Namely, his father Amaziah; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "slept with his fathers — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The meaning is, that Amaziah did not perfect his conquest of Edom, but left some work there for his son to do.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14:15-22 Amaziah survived his conqueror fifteen years. He was slain by his own subjects. Azariah, or Uzziah, seems to have been very young when his father was slain. Though the years of his reign are reckoned from that event, he was not fully made king till eleven years afterwards.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Elath, or Eloth (marginal reference ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), was near Ezion-Geber, in the Gulf of Akabah. It had been lost to the Jews on the revolt of Edom from Joram ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Uzziah's re-establishment of the place, rendered possible by his father's successes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 14:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was one of his first acts, and seems to imply a desire to renew the commercial projects which Solomon had successfully carried out, and which Jehoshaphat had vainly attempted ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "22. He built Elath—fortified that seaport. It had revolted with the rest of Edom, but was now recovered by Uzziah. His father, who did not complete the conquest of Edom, had left him that work to do.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
