  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He built Elath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Elath (also written ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Eloth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was at the northern extremity of the Gulf of Akabah. It is said in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to have belonged to Edom, but at this time Judah was powerful enough to secure a road through Edom for trade purposes, and so extend the sway of their kingdom to the same point southward which they had occupied in the days of Solomon. Between that time and this, Elath had most likely fallen into decay. Hence the mention of ‘building’, which of course means restoration. (See on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and restored it to Judah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] As it had been in the days of Solomon. We need not suppose that more was done than to secure a passage through Edom between Elath and Jerusalem. Edom was of small use to Judah, but a port on the Red Sea was a great acquisition.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "after that the king slept with his fathers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This is another of those vague notices which indicate an unusual state of things in Judah at this period. It would almost seem as though Azariah had been put in authority, if not on the throne, before the death of his father, and that he had been making his plans beforehand, only waiting for his father’s death to carry them out. He was without doubt a popular monarch, for it is said (verse 21) that all Judah agreed on him for king.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 22.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "He built Elath, and restored it to Judah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " On the position of Elath, or Eloth, and its importance, see the comment on 1 Kings 9:26. It had been the headquarters of Solomon's fleet (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and again of Jehoshaphat's (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but had been, of course, recovered by the Edomites when they revolted (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Azariah's re-occupation seems to imply an intention on his part of, renewing the old Red Sea trade. By \"built ' in this passage we must understand \"rebuilt\" or (as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 11:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") \"fortified.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "After that the king slept with his fathers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Keil is probably right in understanding this to mean \"immediately after he had ascended the throne,\" or \"as soon as ever his father was dead\" (see the comment on ver. 19). His further military successes will be considered in the comment on his reign, as sketched in the next chapter. 2 Kings 14:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Immediately after his ascent of the throne, Uzziah built, i.e., fortified, Elath, the Idumaean port (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 9:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and restored it to Judah again. It is evident from this that Uzziah completed the renewed subjugation of Edom which his father had begun. The position in which this notice stands, immediately after his ascent of the throne and before the account of the duration and character of his reign, may be explained in all probability from the importance of the work itself, which not only distinguished the commencement of his reign, but also gave evident of its power. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]